    <h2 id="why-fat">Why CoQ10 Needs Fat to Work</h2>

    <p>CoQ10 is a <strong>lipophilic (fat-loving) molecule</strong>. Its chemical structure includes a long isoprenoid tail that makes it insoluble in water but highly soluble in fats and oils. This chemistry dictates how your body absorbs it: CoQ10 cannot cross your intestinal wall as a free molecule. Instead, it must be packaged into <strong>micelles</strong> — tiny spherical structures formed by bile acids and dietary fats in the small intestine. Without fat in your meal, no micelles form, and CoQ10 passes through your digestive tract largely unabsorbed.</p>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A 2018 study in the <em>Journal of Clinical Pharmacy and Therapeutics</em> measured plasma CoQ10 levels after identical 200mg doses taken (a) on an empty stomach, (b) with a low-fat breakfast, and (c) with a high-fat breakfast. The high-fat group showed <strong>3x higher peak blood levels</strong> than the empty-stomach group — making the difference between a working supplement and an expensive placebo.</p>
      <cite>Journal of Clinical Pharmacy and Therapeutics, 2018 — CoQ10 bioavailability with food</cite>
    </div>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card"><strong>Bile acid dependence</strong><p>Eating fat triggers your gallbladder to release bile — bile acts as an emulsifier that breaks up fat droplets and carries CoQ10 into absorbable micelles.</p></div>
      <div class="info-card"><strong>Micelle formation</strong><p>Micelles are microscopic "transport vehicles" that ferry fat-soluble molecules (CoQ10, vitamins A, D, E, K) from your gut into your bloodstream.</p></div>
      <div class="info-card"><strong>3-5g fat minimum</strong><p>Research shows at least 3-5 grams of dietary fat is needed to meaningfully improve CoQ10 absorption. More fat (10g+) optimizes it further.</p></div>
      <div class="info-card"><strong>Fasting reduces absorption</strong><p>Empty stomach CoQ10 absorption is only 20-30% of fed-state absorption. This is why intermittent fasters should take CoQ10 with their first meal.</p></div>
    </div>

